observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the establishment of subsidiary ledgers for the respective accounts;
Exert all efforts to reconcile and analyze the accounts to determine whether they warrant an adjustment in accordance with existing COA rules and regulations;
Furnish certification and/or reasons why the books of accounts/records/financial statements/schedules and supporting documents cannot be located; and
Require proper turn-over of documents/pending work from officials and employees retiring/separating from office/service to ensure completeness of records.

We recommended that the Management:
exert efforts to locate all necessary documents and pursue the titling of the remaining parcel(s) of land in the name of the Municipality;
instruct the Property Officer and Municipal Accountant to regularly conduct reconciliation of their reports so that any discrepancy noted could be promptly adjusted and reconciled.

We recommended:

the Inventory Committee to conduct inventory count of all the properties of the municipalities including, but not limited to, Lands, Land Improvements, Public Infrastructures, Building, Machineries and Equipment, Transportation Equipment, Furniture and Fixtures, Books, Construction in Progress, and other PPEs;

the Inventory Committee to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment and Report on the Physical Count of Inventories in accordance with the instructions provided under Appendixes 60 to 66 of the Government Accounting Manual (GAM) for LGUs Volume II;

the Inventory Committee and Accounting Office reconcile the results of the count with the property and accounting record; and

the management ensure that the supply/property officer maintain supply/property cards and the accounting office maintain supply ledger cards/schedules of all the properties and inventories.

We recommended the management to:

Identify the details of long outstanding Due from NGAs amounting P25,042.29; 

determine the collectibility of the accounts and send collection letters to concerned individuals or their heirs; 

exhaust all applicable legal remedies to collect; 

request for write off from COA if remedies fail; and 

effect adjustments in the books.

